A finite-state transducer is a state machine that reads an input tape and writes to an output tape [117]. A probabilistically weighted finite-state transducer is the same, but its behavior is stochastic [110]. For the purposes of bioinformatics sequence analysis, a transducer can be thought of as being just like a Pair HMM; except where a Pair HMM’s transition and emission probabilities have been normalized so as to describe joint probabilities, a transducer’s probabilities are normalized so as to describe conditional probabilities like the entries of matrix M(t) (Eq. 2). More specifically, if i and j are sequences, then one can define the matrix entry A
